This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of computational linguistics (cs.CL) because it deals with the classification of semantic relations between words. It also uses unsupervised corpus-based features, which are commonly used in natural language processing. Additionally, it could belong to the sub-category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) because it uses a machine learning algorithm (Random Forest) to classify the relations. The use of a machine learning algorithm also makes it likely to belong to the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also involves cross-validation, which is a common technique in information retrieval (cs.IR) and machine learning. Finally, it could belong to the sub-category of computational complexity (cs.CC) because it deals with the complexity of learning taxonomical semantic relations.
